        "possibleIdentity": "Louis Silverman was a materials engineer, metallurgist, and ceramist active during the late 1960s and early 1970s. He was a member of the American Ceramic Society and was professionally associated with the Victory Engineering Corporation (VECO), a manufacturer of specialized electronic components such as thermistors and varistors. During this period, he resided in Clifton, New Jersey, and worked for the company's facility, which was located in Springfield, New Jersey. His expertise in ceramics and metal oxides was relevant to the production of temperature-sensing devices. Silverman is documented as being associated with Experiments in Art and Technology (E.A.T.), a non-profit organization that facilitated collaborations between the technical and artistic communities. He likely served as a technical consultant or collaborator, offering his knowledge of materials science and sensor technology to artists through the E.A.T. Technical Services program.",
